🛠️ Technical Troubleshooting: Resolving Telemetry Gaps
During the setup of the SOC pipeline, a "Visibility Gap" was identified where network activities on the Windows victim (10.0.0.20) were not appearing in Splunk. The following steps were taken to remediate the issue:

Network Path Validation: Verified connectivity between the Kali Linux attack node and Windows Victim using ping and nc -nvz. Identified that DNS resolution was failing in the isolated subnet; resolved by enforcing numeric-only (-n) flags across all attack tools.

Endpoint Telemetry Tuning: Discovered that the initial Sysmon configuration was too restrictive. Deployed a custom, permissive XML schema (onmatch="exclude") to ensure the capture of Event ID 3 (Network Connection) for all system processes.

Service Privilege Escalation: Identified a permission bottleneck where the Splunk Universal Forwarder (UF) lacked access to the Sysmon Operational channel. Reconfigured the Splunk Forwarder service to run under the LocalSystem context.

ACL Remediation: Manually adjusted the Channel Access Control List (ACL) using the wevtutil command to grant the Event Log Readers group explicit permissions to read the Sysmon event stream.

Indexer Sync (Fishbucket Reset): Cleared the Splunk UF fishbucket checkpoints to force a re-indexing of the Sysmon logs, ensuring that "lost" events during the configuration phase were successfully backfilled into the SIEM.

Result: Successfully established a real-time data pipeline, confirmed by the ingestion of Nmap scan telemetry and automated brute-force alerts.


🛠️ Technical Troubleshooting: Simulating Brute Force on Windows 11
During the simulation phase, I encountered significant challenges generating and ingesting Event ID 4625 (Failed Logon) from the Kali Linux attack node. Modern Windows security features were effectively "silencing" the attack. I performed the following remediation steps:

Enabling Audit Policies: Windows 11 does not log failed attempts by default. I utilized auditpol to manually enable "Failure" auditing for the Logon/Logoff subcategory, forcing the OS to generate telemetry for failed credentials.

Bypassing NLA (Network Level Authentication): Identified that RDP attacks were being dropped at the network layer. I disabled NLA and modified RDP settings to allow the "handshake" to reach the authentication service.

Disabling SMB Hardening & Rate Limiting: Windows 11 (24H2+) features a default SMB Authentication Rate Limiter. I utilized PowerShell to set InvalidAuthenticationDelayTimeInMs to 0 and disabled mandatory SMB signing, preventing the Windows VM from "timing out" the Kali node during automated attempts.

Protocol Adaptation (Legacy vs. Modern): Discovered that legacy tools like Hydra often failed the NetBIOS handshake due to SMBv1/v2 deprecation. Successfully pivoted to NetExec (NXC) to utilize modern SMBv3 dialects, resulting in successful Logon Type 3 (Network) event generation.

Security Log Onboarding: Reconfigured the Splunk Universal Forwarder inputs.conf to specifically monitor the WinEventLog://Security channel, which is separate from the Sysmon channel, ensuring failed logins were indexed in the SIEM.

Logon Type Differentiation: Validated the difference between Logon Type 2 (local keyboard attempts) and Logon Type 3 (network-based attacks from Kali) to ensure the SOC dashboard accurately identified remote threats.

Result: Achieved a consistent telemetry stream from the attack node to Splunk, enabling the creation of a high-fidelity "Brute Force Monitor" dashboard.

